<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>is a highly branched, perennial grass that has a bushlike appearance. Its coarse, rigid culms reach 100 cm in length, and they may be erect or decumbent. Seed production is low and seedling establishment rare. It reproduces primarily by rhizomes and tillers. It is the most drought-tolerant of the <i>Pleuraphis </i>species (Matthews 2000b). This warm-season and droughttolerant grass, is rarely found in the western Mojave Desert where summer rainfall is negligible. Much of the botanical literature uses the name <i>Hilaria rigida. <br/>
<br/>
Pleuraphis rigida </i>is common in the understory of several shrub- and tree-dominated alliances, but in this alliance the grass has more cover than do the shrubs. It acts as a nurse plant to <i>Agave deserti, Ferocactus cylindraceus, </i>and shrubs (Matthews 2000b). The alliance is relatively rare in the stateâ€™s deserts, and its range probably has decreased with prolonged heavy grazing (Desert Workshop 2000). It has a bimodal distribution in which it occurs as open stands around dune margins and other sandy areas at low elevations, and as closed stands on upland slopes and bajadas at middle elevations where growth is reduced on clays. In dune areas, it gives way to open stands of the <i>Panicum urvilleanum </i>alliance on deeper sand deposits. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
