    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-b). Stands are rare and restricted to sandy substrates in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and in Coachella Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ac-d, Ah-p). Stands mostly occur in the eastern and southern subsections (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005, Thomas et al. 2004). Sandy-substrate stands are typical, such as those found at Cronese Lakes, Devilâ€™s Playground, Kelso Dunes, Pinto Basin, and along Razor Road. Upland rocky stands exist in Clipper and Lanfair valleys. Some have been grazed, burned, and contain disturbance-related shrubs. Stands in the Marine Corps Air-Ground Combat Center (Minnich et al. 1993) lack warm-season rains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands occur on both sandy and upland sites throughout the section, but upland sites are uncommon and are largely restricted to sandy areas, dune fields, and narrow stringers along small drainages and washes. Stands exist near Cadiz Lake and Cadiz-Vidal Valleys (Evens and Hartman 2007), Ford Dry Lakes, as well in Palen and Rice valleys.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bp). Stands are restricted to the western desert margin in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park in Coyote Canyon, Earthquake Valley, and Potrero areas. They show the effects of long-term grazing and high fire frequencies resulting from human-caused ignitions and high annual grass cover. Some shrub-steppes have emergent <i>Senegalia greggii, Cylindropuntia</i> spp., and <i>Yucca schidigera</i> or disturbance-related subshrubs such as <i>Ambrosia salsola</i> and <i>Lotus scoparius,</i> which are likely better placed in the <i>Cylindropuntia acanthocarpa - Pleuraphis rigida</i> Alliance.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Livestock grazing and altered fire frequencies have affected upland non-sandy stands, while the non-native <i>Brassica tournefortii </i>frequently invades the sandy stands. In all stands, <i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>appears sensitive to fire when dry. Managers need to identify and monitor change in time and with disturbance, particularly in mid elevation, non-sandy stands. </div>
</div>

    

    

